5- Mount acquired images using Arsenal Image Mounter (AIM)

The last step in this lab is to learn how to mount images so you can analyze them. Many available tools can mount images. However, we will stick to the most popular one, Arsenal Image Mounter. 

Once you open the tool, you will be presented with the following interface.

 

AIM interface - (zoom in)

The First step is to click on "Mount disk image". An "Open file dialog" will appear to select the disk image.

As you can see, AIM supports a wide range of image types:

 

AIM Supported Image Types - (zoom in)

Select the image you want to mount and check the options you want per your preference. Greyed-out options are available only in Pro-version.

 

AIM mounting options - (zoom in)

  1. The default option is to mount the drive in a read-only mode.
  2. Mount the image in a temporary-write mode. You can write data and modify the image content. However, all changes will be discarded at the end to keep the original image intact.
  3. NTFS file system employs security restrictions to critical files used by the OS (e.g., $MFT and $USNJRNL). By checking this option in Arsenal Image Mounter, the tool will bypass these restrictions and make these critical files accessible to the analyst.
  4. Unlike temporary-write mode, this mode will write changes permanently to the original image.
  5. Same as point 3 but with write permissions.
  6. Specify the sector size of the original disk (where the image was captured from).
  7. By default, each mounted drive will have a unique disk signature. Sometimes you may need to mount multiple instances of the same image but with different attributes (e.g., read-only, writeable..etc.). By checking this option in Arsenal Image Mounter, the tool will create a fake signature for each drive so you can mount as many instances (of the same image) as you need. 
  8. Mount the image as a removable USB.
  9. Automount previously mounted image at AIM startup.

After mounting the image, you will see it listed in AIM main window as follows:

 

AIM - (zoom in)

  1. Path to the image
  2. Mount point: Assigned drive letter.
  3. Partition layout: partition types (MBR or GPT)
  4. Hard disk signature: Signature of the hard-disk
  5. Disk size: the size of the original drive the mounted image was acquired from.

Then you can browse to the "Mount Point" where you will find the image content.

 

Mounted image content - (zoom in)
